  <static seed="277" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicMath/FractionApplication/FractionSubtractionWordProblems50.pg">
    <statement><p>Cheryl and Kim are sharing a pizza. Cheryl ate <m>{{\frac{2}{9}}}</m> of the pizza, and Kim ate <m>{{\frac{1}{6}}}</m> of the pizza. How much more pizza did Cheryl eat than Kim?</p>
<p>Cheryl ate <fillin characters="10" name="AnSwEr0001"/> more of the pizza than Kim ate.</p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>{\frac{1}{18}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To find the difference of two numbers, we use subtraction:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ 
\begin{aligned}[t]
   {{\frac{2}{9}}} - {{\frac{1}{6}}} 
      \amp = \frac{2 \cdot 2}{9 \cdot 2}-\frac{1 \cdot 3}{6 \cdot 3} \\
      \amp = \frac{4}{18} - \frac{3}{18} \\
      \amp = \frac{4-3}{18} \\
      
      \amp = {{\frac{1}{18}}}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Cheryl ate <m>{{\frac{1}{18}}}</m> more of the pizza than Kim ate.</p>
</solution>
